value.value: Appendage girdle complex that when present, encompasses the pectoral appendage and half of the pectoral girdle.
Anatomical group that consists of the soft and skeletal tissues of the appendicular region of the body and the appendage proper.

definition.value: It is still called a complex when one of the two parts is missing (?) There are fossil fishes with only an outgrowth (no record of a girdle), including thelodonts (which have a suprabranchial fin) as well as some anaspids which have a distinctive 'paired fin' (with differing published assertions on whether it's homologous to a pec fin or pelvic fin or both or neither).  There are many fishes and other vertebrates with only a girdle and no outgrowth.

value.value: Appendage girdle complex that when present, encompasses the pelvic appendage and the pelvic girdle.
Skeletal subdivision that is part of the limb.
Skeletal subdivision that is part of the paired limb/fin.
Skeletal subdivision that is part of the appendage girdle region.

An organism subdivision that encompasses the region containing the pectoral or pelvic girdle. Note that this includes both the skeletal elements and associated tissues (integument, muscle, etc). There are only two instances of  appendage girdle regions per organism.
Subdivision of lower limb or fin which links the limb/fin to the body[FMA,modified]. There is only one instance of the pelvic girdle region per organism.

definition.value: Note that this class describes the central subdivision of the pelvic girdle complex, NOT the skeleton within.

value.value: An organism subdivision that includes the pectoral girdle skeleton. Note that this includes both the skeletal elements and associated tissues (integument, muscle, etc). There is only one instance of the pectoral girdle region per organism.

definition.value: Note that this class describes the central subdivision of the pectoral girdle complex, NOT the skeleton within.

value.value: Skeletal system which consists of the appendicular skeleton plus associated joints.
Bone element that is adjacent to the notochord.
Bone element that is located on the surface of a cartilage element.
Proximal element of the limb skeleton consisting of the femur and humerus in the forelimb stylopodium and hindlimb stylopodium respectively.
Section of the forelimb skeleton located between the stylopodium and the autopodium.
Distal section of the limb skeleton, consisting of the anterior autopodium or posterior autopodium.
Limb skeleton subdivision consisting of endochondral bones increasing the freedom of movement of the autopodia, and located between zeugopodia and autopodia.
Endochondral bone complex located between the mesopodium and the acropodium and consisting of the metacarpals or metatarsals.
Endochondral terminal bones at the distalmost end of the autopodium, consisting of the phalanges.

definition.value: sometimes mistakenly used to include the metapodium
Used to describe a location that consists of a number of Regions but where the order is not known. e.g. the oddly named order() keyword in a INSDC file.
The 'both strands position' indicates a region that is best described as being on 'both' strands of a double-stranded sequence, rather than one or the other.
The C-terminus is the end of an amino acid chain (protein or polypeptide), terminated by a free carboxyl group (-COOH).

Sometimes a location of a feature is defined by a collection of regions e.g. join() and order() in INSDC records. One should always try to model the semantics more accurately than this, these are fallback options to encode legacy data.
A position that is exactly known.
The position is on the forward (positive, 5' to 3') strand. Shown as a '+' in GFF3 and GTF.
A position that lacks exact data.

This indicates that a feature is between two other positions that are both known exactly and that are next to each other. An example is a restriction enzyme cutting site. The cut is after one position and before the other position (hence, in between).
Use when you have an idea of the range in which you can find the position, but you cannot be sure about the exact position.
As an ordered list of regions (but the list might not be complete).

Should be used when the location of a region is defined by an ordered list of Regions. However, try to avoid using these types in favor of using more explicit semantics about why the order is important.

The position of the starting amino-acid a protein or polypeptide terminated by an amino acid with a free amine group (-NH2). The convention for writing peptide sequences is to put the N-terminus on the left and write the sequence from N- to C-terminus. Instances of this class are often used when the reference sequence is not complete
The position is known to be one of the more detailed positions listed by the location predicate.
Superclass for the general concept of a position on a sequence. The sequence is designated with the reference predicate.
A region describes a length of sequence with a start position and end position that represents a feature on a sequence, e.g. a gene.
The position is on the reverse (complement, 3' to 5') strand of the sequence. Shown as '-' in GTF and GFF3.

Part of the coordinate system denoting on which strand the feature can be found. If you do not yet know which stand the feature is on, you should tag the position with just this class. If you know more you should use one of the subclasses. This means a region described with a '.' in GFF3. A GFF3 unstranded position does not have this type in FALDO -- those are just a 'position'.
Indicates the wavelength in nm at which photoreactive proteins such as opsins and DNA photolyases show maximal absorption.
Amino acid(s) involved in the activity of an enzyme.
Description of an enzyme, transporter and microbial transcription regulation mechanism.
Information relevant to allergenic proteins.
Description of the existence of related protein sequences produced by alternative splicing of the same gene or by the use of alternative initiation codons.
Description of sequence variants produced by alternative splicing.
Beta strand regions within the experimentally determined protein structure
Binding site for any chemical group (co-enzyme, prosthetic group, etc.).
Biophysical and physicochemical data such as pH dependence, temperature dependence, kinetic parameters, redox potentials, and maximal absorption.
Description of the use of a specific protein in a biotechnological process.
A chapter from a book.
Description of the reactions catalyzed by an enzyme.
Warning about possible errors and/or grounds for confusion.
